segments.text: Mr. C.A.
Bonin, side two.
We were talking about the school board.
And in 1944, you became on the school board.
What facilities did you have at that time?
There's some wooden buildings.
They're all gone now.
They're over here where the present school and where the city.
That was the one that fronts on Jersey.
The city owns that now.
But the school owns the building back of it.
So in 1944, there were only wooden shacks in that area?
Or wooden buildings, I'm sorry.
After 1940, those wooden buildings were built.
See, that's when we were ordered off the campus.
Right.
And I think all those buildings are gone now except the old gymnasium.
In 49, do you remember that the school district decided to build
a more permanent building?
It's the one that the city owns now.
It's the one that is the community center now?
Yeah.
Can you tell me a little bit about how you and the superintendent went about deciding on how to build this building?
We visited a lot of campuses, high school campuses.
And I imagine this, which is now the city building, was built according to the ideas that he and I picked up around these different campuses.
What we liked, what we didn't like, and what we could afford and all that sort of thing.
this building and the Lincoln School were both built out of a bond issue of a little over, I think it was $110,000 that we had to work with.
The school board's bond election?
It was the school board?
Yeah.
Or was it the city?
No, the school board.
Was it at this time that you had to double the tax rate on the property in order to get enough money?
No, that was when we ordered off the campus.
That was Bill Sparks and I.
We were the main ones and we were active when the rest of the school board was
left it up to us to do the work.
But in 49, when you built the school that is presently the community center, you had a $110,000 bond?
Yeah, a little over $100,000, if I remember.
To provide for?
Both schools, one down in Lincoln and here.
Lincoln was the Negro facility?
Why were they separate?
We just grew up that way.
It had always been that way?
Always been that way.
before the integration of the black schools and the white schools.
Where were other facilities?
Do you remember other negro facilities before Lincoln School was built?
Well, I remember there was a school there for the negroes.
But it was kind of ramshackle.
Where was that located?
Right where they, approximately where the Lincoln School is now.
Oh, okay.
So they had an area where Lincoln is, and in 1949 they built Lincoln School also.
Yeah.
Do you remember when the schools were integrated here in College Station?
No, but I'm in and you can find out.
It wasn't too long ago, you know.
It wasn't too long ago?
No.
I think you can find that over at the city.
Did some of College Station students go to Bryan, to the Bryan School District?
A few did, not many.
How would you compare the two districts?
That's hard to do.
They were an old, well-organized school district.
We were young.
No money to spend on school, but we had good teachers.
And that's mostly what a school's made of, the teachers and the people that build the schools and so on.
We were a pretty select group out here, mostly faculty members on the campus.
Mr. Gabbard and George Wilcox and I are all on the A&M faculty and had some idea of what the school would be like and all that sort of thing.
In a place as old as Bryan, you get all kinds of actions to deal with, you know.
The Mexicans and the Negroes and the whites all have a little different interest in the school.
Out here, it is pretty much our school.
Pretty much homogenous.
I had read about, and I need some clarification if you know this incident, where the Bryan School District
encouraged somebody to become the superintendent of a college station?
Yeah.
With the purpose of weakening?
He admitted later that he was sent out here to take over or bring our school into Brian.
Do you remember who that was?
I can't think of his name.
It was Bunning.
His name was Bunning.
Bunning?
Bunning.
And he later was county superintendent.
Do you remember what years that was?
Well, I was on the school board.
We got off the campus in 1940.
When I went on the school board, all the rest of the directors were Baptists.
a fellow by the name of Breeland, Jim Breeland, went to Mississippi, I think, from here.
They were, that group were pretty much in charge of the school at that time.
And you can imagine the position I was in.
vote as one man.
And you had the dissenting vote most of the time.
Dissenting vote, yeah.
A little later.
took control of the school, but it was pretty tough going for a while.
Were their decisions arbitrary in any way?
Oh, they just voted together.
One would vote and then the rest of them would vote.
The same way?
Do you know what period that was, what time, what years?
Well, I went on the school ward in 1944.
Four or five years after that.
I didn't have much to say.
How many members made up the school board?
How many people were on the school board?
I think it was seven.
Seven?
I think it was five or seven.
Did Mr. Bunting do any damage to the school system when he did?
He made a statement.
There was only one good boy in 40, so the school
the boys in the school immediately organized us as the 40 boys that he had in mind.
And of course, he said what he wanted.
He delighted in dissension and all that sort of thing.
dissension within the school?
Yeah.
It was a pretty rough time.
How long was he superintendent?
About four years, I think.
Something like that.
Then he became county superintendent.
But he wasn't able to... No.
As soon as they got rid of him, the school fell into
Who was the next superintendent after Bunting?
Well, it came from out in Central Texas and was superintendent for about three or four years.
down in the north edge of the Edwards Plateau near San Angelo.
He was a very, very nice gentleman.
Our school began to grow about that time.
Didn't have somebody in the school system fighting to bring it into Bryan.
Did Mr. Bunting make an active attempt to bring the school district into Bryan?
We never knew what he was doing.
We knew what he said.
which indicated that is what he was working for.
Do you remember the years that this happened?
It was in the 40s, early 40s.
Okay.
I can't give you the exact year.
That's fine.
Just an approximate date is fine.
Is there anything else you'd like to add about the school system?
Basically, you're my best source as far as the school system is concerned that I haven't asked you about that might be important.
A year or two ago, I could have helped you a great deal.
What you've told me so far has been a lot of help.
Well, I hope so.
Your questions have helped me.
Help you remember?
Yeah, put your finger on things.
If you don't remember anything anymore about the school, I'd like to talk about the lawsuit that was brought against the city concerning the legality of serving both the city and the state.
Do you remember that?
Yes.
I served three years on the city council during that time.
Mm-hmm.
Mr. Anderson, not Frank Anderson, but DA Anderson, traveled all over the state and got that law, got them to do away with that law, which committed
He attacked on the school system.
It also attacked the school system?
Oh, that's right.
You couldn't serve on the school board.
Yeah.
And that's right.
Do you remember who brought the suit against the city?
Boyant, wasn't it?
Yeah, Boyant.
Why do you think he... Well, Boyant's...
They owned a lot of land around here, and whenever the school had to buy more land, they had to buy it from the boys.
Is that right, Alice?
Yeah, and I don't know why, but they seemed to have got across roads with the city and the school, it seemed like.
Well, they owned all that land north of the campus.
They had problems with the taxes.
With the tax?
The taxes.
Did they not want to pay?
They were pretty bad about paying the taxes.
I see.
But you don't recall why he would bring it against the city, the suit?
He was, when Mr. D.A.
Anderson was mayor, he gave him an awful lot of trouble.
And I can't remember why that was.
But I know that he gave him a lot of trouble.
I know they had a city meeting.
Interesting people.
Encouraged people to come.
sort of counteract the Boyd effect.
Was there someone of Boyd's on the city council around that time?
There was one on the...
I think there was.
They kept them down on everything they wanted to do.
Mr. Anderson was so interested in getting these lands for the parks at that time.
He's the one that really pushed...
ahead of time for us to have parkland around here.
And they were kind of holding back on these things.
I see.
They weren't interested in... No, no, they just weren't aggressive.
I don't think they could see that the city was going to grow that much.
And they just didn't seem to see those things.
I know he asked a group of us over there one Sunday, and I think he had other groups of interested citizens to talk to us about it.
to see if we could get behind him on it because he was having such a hard time with these people.
And then there was one man that really wasn't too well educated himself that was always on the council back then.
I can't think of his name now.
They had the districts different then.

people that area for over there near where the city hall used to be over near the boy at land and and that man was always on there too and the boy had him under their finger you don't remember his name though i ought to be able to let her sit there okay
whenever you think of it.
If I do.
Well, how did this lawsuit affect the city?
How did it affect the government of the city?
Well, it affected the government of all cities.
And that's what Dee Anderson traveled all over the state to interest other cities in our problem.
And they repealed it.
your college within the city, because the greater number of people that would be interested in being on the council are employed by the state.
And they could not hold a council position if they were employed by the state, even if they didn't pay the council, which they don't here at College Station.
But you see, they supposedly couldn't collect the salary.
But it even held true if you weren't getting a salary at the same.
I know they had that same problem.
Down there at Angleton, they have a son that's a lawyer down there, and he's a city lawyer.
And they had two men that they had had on the city council.
Maybe one of them was on the school board.
I don't know.
But they had been paid, I think, around $100 a month.
And it caused a real problem because
They said they had to pay back the money they collected.
Isn't that awful?
Is there a college in England?
No, but these were school teachers.
Oh, on the school board.
Yeah, and they were school teachers, some of these people that were on the council.
So they were serving Texas.
So they were serving Texas.
They were paid by Texas at these schools.
And the council.
Oh, I see.
See, they were getting state money.
So it would affect a lot of cities.
Yes, and especially here back then in the times when Daddy was on there, they were all people from the university, and we didn't have many people out here that worked with the university.
And so every one of the people on the council were, I guess every one of them was at that time, no, Don Dale, is he on there now?
But most of them were employed by the university.
My husband was 75 years old when they pushed him up.
Oh, I didn't realize that.
And Dr. Lindsey, he was 72.
Both of them replaced two men that were employed by the university.
And what's his name again?
Fred Anderson.
Fred Bryson.
Is he still alive?
No.
No.
No, he isn't alive.
No, there are too many of those people that would have been good ones for you to talk to are gone now.
That's too bad.
This is our next-door neighbor.
My husband was on the first city council.
It would have been wonderful to talk to Mr. Gabbard.
We've talked about him.
Well, do you feel like the issue was valid at all?
It was a state law, but they got it taken off.
It was him?
That's what D.A.
Anderson traveled all over the state to.
To get people to vote it off.
Were these people... Oh, I see.
Oh, it was in a constitutional amendment and people voted?
Yes, they tried and then they had a chance to vote it off.
And he encouraged... Well, that was wonderful.
He really...
He did it almost single-handed, I think.
He traveled all over.
He's done a lot of good things for the city.
Do you know why he never...
I know he had resigned during that period.
Do you know why he never ran again for mayor after that?
When he could?
When he could.
So, when you... Can you tell me about your becoming a councilman?
It was something that you were asked to do, is that right?
Andy Anderson asked him to run.
And at that time, he wasn't getting off right away.
And right after
there to back him up with someone that knew about everything, Mr. Anderson.
But he found he had to get off, too.
So when these men were resigning from the council, Mr. Anderson asked you to run in a special election?
Is that right?
Yeah.
And right after that, he had to resign then, too.
Yes, I remember that.
He did resign, yeah.
He hadn't at the time.
I don't remember why that was.
Well, we know he resigned.
Yeah, he resigned shortly after that.
Really, before you were elected, though.
Yeah.
That was it.
He did all he could before he had to get off.
Except my husband so much that he had a mild stroke.
Oh, is that right?
Yeah, just... Yeah, it was in 71, wasn't it?
Yes.
Yes, it was.
Then who became mayor after Mr. Anderson was signed?
Oh, Dick Hervey.
Yeah, Hervey.
Dick Hervey.
You know him, don't you?
I don't know if he was connected with the bank.
I don't know if he is anymore.
How did the council meetings operate when you were on the council?
How did they operate?
What were they like?
Did citizens attend?
There were always some there.
Were there... Breland was involved in the school, wasn't he?
Yes, that was long before that time.
That was when you were at school then.
Yes, I was about 75 years old.
Yeah, when you went on to college.
Were there, was the council pretty much, how can I say this, harmonious or did you find that there was disagreement among the council on different issues?
Well, I suppose there was some disagreement, but when I was on the council, it was pretty well in agreement.
We were talking just a minute ago about the recreation program.
Was this a time when the city devoted more of its energy into providing parks and things for the citizens?
The council has been pretty generally favorable to the parks and that sort of thing.
They really have done most of the developing of the parks since you were off of the council.
In recent years, they've done so much of the developing of the parks.
My daughter is on the council now.
That's right.
Would you say, though, that Anderson...
He's the one that really...
As far as I can remember, he really spearheaded the whole thing about the parks.
He may have something different to tell you on that, but that's the way I see it.
If it hadn't been for him, they might not have picked up land where they did back then.
And that was the thing that he was working so hard at when the Boyettes were making it hard for him.
So he could see the growth that College Station was?
Yes.
And then, of course,
being in the kind of work that he was in, he knew the need for that sort of thing.
Do you remember the Pinnell plan, a specific plan for growth of College Station during your period on the council?
Wasn't that after you were on the Pinnell?
It was after.
I believe this is one of the first times they set down a specific plan for College Station.
What did they call it, the 2000?
The one now.
Yeah.
Yeah, that's the one now.
I think this was called 701, Plan 701.
That was after you were on the council.
OK. Zoning has always been important in College Station.
We had a zoning law since the city was incorporated.
And do you remember why did the people want zoning?
Well, they had people like Mr. Gabbard on there that knew the necessary things.
Yeah, Mr. Gabbard and George Wilcox.
It was a college-oriented group, and they had more vision than the ordinary person would have, things like that.
And they had also seen...
what had happened to Brian about something.
Why don't you think Brian zoned?
They never have.
They weren't far-sighted enough to see ahead of time.
And then you get into it, you know, and there's... Yeah, there are always people that are...
It's against their interest because of certain real estate developments and that sort of thing.
So they... Well, I guess you read the papers and
followed their reasoning and so on.
But Bryan had more of the real estate developer people in their town, whereas College Station... Not now.
I think now we have about as many out here.
But back then, really, Bryan was run by a few families almost, it seems like.
You know, the old families.
And they saw things one way and that was the way it was done.
Do you know of any of the names of the families?
I didn't know.
So many of them are gone now, and things have changed in Bryant since it's got in the hands of more people now.
More diversified type of people than they used to have.
Everybody had to start out in Bryan.
There wasn't anything out here except on the campus when we came here.
And then some people had started a little development around what is Dexter Park now, or Bryson Park.
And there were about 25 houses out there, and that's all of us here.
And the few houses that were on the campus.
Now the city has grown clear out to be.
What's the name of that?
The Texas Speedway?
Well, not quite the Texas Speedway, but... Yeah, it's almost out there.
Yeah, it's almost out there.
The East Bypass.
Yeah, see, that's the only way we can go over to the south and west.
But you see, Brian looked at everybody connected with the university as trenches.
That was the way to follow it.
or anything like this.
And one neighbor next door to me, who was very nice, she said, you know, they just think that way about the university people.
Of course, it was college then.
And she said, so she said, they can't be bothered with you.
And that's the attitude they take.
And so then they kind of would screen them out as far as letting them give any emphasis to anything that was going on in there.
Why would they think college professors were transient since they usually stayed and worked at a university?
Yeah, well, of course, some did just stay for a little while.
But for some reason or other, they had that attitude.
And of course, the housing was such a problem then.
And people weren't building their own homes in there then.
They were in red houses.
And the housing situation was terrible when they came here.
The first house we lived in out here, it's hard to tell the difference between the atmosphere in the house and outside the house.
There just weren't any homes around the campus, right?
No.
Those were on the campus, owned by the state, and those were given preference.
some heads and all heads didn't even get out of there, and deans and people like that.
The Gabbers lived on the campus, the folks next door, and she was just saying the other day, she said, you know, that was such an undemocratic way of doing it.
She said, here were the people that were on the lowest salaries having to struggle
Of course, the rents were low everywhere then because salaries were low, like $30 a month and so forth.
And that's all they were worth.
And that's all they were worth.
But she said, on the campus, she said she always understood that the deans didn't have to pay anything for their houses.
And she said, we paid $21 for our house.
And they were given months of privileges
And two, the ones that were ranked a little higher up.
That's interesting.
It is, isn't it?
So it was a good idea when they decided to get those off.
You know, as things developed, it was just a very undemocratic way of doing it.
Do you remember while you were on the council any big problems that the council had to deal with?
I don't think we had any problems.
The college station has them all now.
Is that right?
Well, it's developed so fast.
40,000 to 50,000 people in the college station now.
And apparently, from other than just around this area, they are recognized as having done a very good job.
of handling this fast growth.
Patsy said they didn't realize it until they got at some of these meetings.
And they've been held up as kind of an example.
That's wonderful.
Handling rapid growth.
But when Mr. Bonham was on the council, it was not growing as rapidly then?
Oh, no.
The thing that made it grow rapidly is one of the things, I should say, is when they brought the girls in here.
No, that just made all the difference in the world.
Everything developed.
Isn't that funny?
Every way.
Eating places.
Yeah.
It's like someone was saying to me on the phone the other day.
She said, you know, back before the last ten years or so, why, she said, if you had company, she said, you had to feed them at home.
There was no taking them out.
We didn't have it.
in any of these places.
Ten years?
Well, maybe it's longer than that.
Not much.
Not much.
Well, it's been longer than that.
Ten years.
Just amazing.
Oh, it is.
Every time you leave College Station and come back, you know, leave for six months or so and come back, it's all different.
Yeah.
Well, do you remember any great achievement or?
We didn't think of them as that.
No, we didn't think.
Just take care of the regular things, regular business.
And we didn't.
And I remember we didn't have as much of the opposition of minor groups.
No, that's true.
The bigger this place gets, the more of that sort of thing.
get people in here from all over.
And this has been one of the biggest problems of late years is people have come in here from cities that have been in existence for 100 years or more.
And they can't understand why we don't have sidewalks everywhere and why we don't have this and don't have that in what's an organized city that's been there for 100 years.
They can't seem to understand it.
And so they kind of make little problems for them.
Can you tell me about the character of the town in the early days?
What people did for entertainment or recreation?
Card parties.
Yes, we had lots of parties.
Big card parties.
And big parties.
And big parties.
Afternoon, evening, both.
I think those things changed with the war and with the place growing and other things that you could go to.
But that pretty much made our own entertainment.
I can remember the first card party we went to.
I think it was at Leland's, wasn't it?
Yeah, probably so.
But there were nice groups here.
Such congenial people, it seems.
And everybody was interested in everybody else.
You know, that was the only, really the only...
recreation they had.
It really was.
Get together in parties, play cards, and have a good time.
The people that you had the parties with still are in contact with, but on the whole, I guess the other...
Most of them are dead.
Oh, are they?
There's so many of them, man.
But would you say that the type of congeniality is not as prominent today?
It is as prominent, but they have so many interests other than that.
I see.
There's so many things they can do.
We have opus and all these things.
They did have, for a good many years, they had what they called, was that town hall they called it then?

and that that was always very nice they brought in you know entertainers and nearly everybody went to those and something like that but that was just kind of a seasonal thing but we uh and and we did so much of our shopping in houston oh really do you what could you say is uh an advantage of having the town that
is influenced by college professors or college people?
Well, I think the first thing is that you have a higher class of people to run the city.
Well, and it makes such a difference in your school.
We had realized that over the years, and that's what all these people, and they were across the street, had children in school, or wanted that in school.
And so many of them like that will tell you that they had older children.
Schools were different then than now.
They didn't have all these drugs, you know, that sort of thing.
And when our children were in high school, the whole school was just back here, under the back of us.
And there were about 150 in high school.
Well, you know, it was just one big family almost.
And everybody knew everybody else.
And if your children went out with someone, you knew who they were with.
Now, they come in from everywhere, you see.
And they tell me that it's quite different.
They've been exposed to so many different things.
A lot of people, as the city did develop earlier,
There were people, traveling men, who covered a large area.
Even when our children were in school, we began to get a few of those families moved in here because they saw what a nice community it was.
And they decided that they could live anywhere in their area.
And so they, just one family, I'm thinking of the girls in David's class, he said, he
